Loan Approval Prediction using Decision Trees

Katlego Mathebula

2026-03-01

Loan Approval Prediction Analysis

1. Project Overview

This analysis explores loan approval prediction using decision tree classification. The goal is to build a predictive model that can classify loan applications as approved or rejected based on financial and employment characteristics.

2. Loading Required Libraries

library(readr)      # For reading CSV files

library(rpart.plot) # For visualizing decision trees
library(caret)      # For data splitting and confusion matrix
library(dplyr)      # For data manipulation
library(ggplot2)    # For data visualization

6. Data Splitting

set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility

# Create stratified train-test split (80% train, 20% test)
train_index <- createDataPartition(
  loan_data$Approval,
  p = 0.8,
  list = FALSE
)

# Split the data
train_data <- loan_data[train_index, ]
test_data <- loan_data[-train_index, ]

# Display split information
cat("Training Set Dimensions:", dim(train_data), "\n")
## Training Set Dimensions: 19201 6
cat("Test Set Dimensions:", dim(test_data), "\n\n")
## Test Set Dimensions: 4799 6

7. Model Training

7.1 Decision Tree Model

# Train decision tree model
dt_model <- rpart(
  Approval ~ Income + Credit_Score + Loan_Amount + DTI_Ratio + Employment_Status,
  data = train_data,
  method = "class",
  control = rpart.control(
    cp = 0.01,       # Complexity parameter to prevent overfitting
    minsplit = 20,   # Minimum observations to split a node
    maxdepth = 30    # Maximum depth of the tree
  )
)

7.2 Visualizing the Decision Tree

# Visualize the decision tree
rpart.plot(
  dt_model,
  type = 2,
  extra = 104,        # Show probability of second class
  fallen.leaves = TRUE,
  main = "Loan Approval Decision Tree",
  box.palette = "BuGn",  # Color palette
  shadow.col = "gray"    # Shadow for depth effect
)

8. Model Evaluation

8.1 Making Predictions

# Make predictions on test data
test_pred <- predict(
  dt_model,
  newdata = test_data,
  type = "class"
)

# Create prediction dataframe
predictions_df <- data.frame(
  Actual = test_data$Approval,
  Predicted = test_pred
)

8.2 Confusion Matrix

# Generate confusion matrix
cm <- confusionMatrix(test_pred, test_data$Approval)

# Print detailed results
cat("Confusion Matrix and Statistics:\n\n")
## Confusion Matrix and Statistics:
print(cm)
## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
## 
##           Reference
## Prediction Approved Rejected

##   Rejected       24     3950
##                                           
##                Accuracy : 0.9819          
##                  95% CI : (0.9777, 0.9855)
##     No Information Rate : 0.8362

##    Detection Prevalence : 0.1719          
##       Balanced Accuracy : 0.9769          
##                                           
##        'Positive' Class : Approved        
## 
# Extract key metrics
accuracy <- cm$overall["Accuracy"]
sensitivity <- cm$byClass["Sensitivity"]
specificity <- cm$byClass["Specificity"]
precision <- cm$byClass["Precision"]
recall <- cm$byClass["Recall"]
f1 <- cm$byClass["F1"]

# Create metrics dataframe
metrics_df <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("Accuracy", "Sensitivity", "Specificity", "Precision", "Recall", "F1-Score"),
  Value = round(c(accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, recall, f1), 4)
)

print("\nPerformance Metrics:")

8.3 Visualizing Confusion Matrix

# Extract confusion matrix values
conf_matrix <- as.data.frame(cm$table)

# Plot confusion matrix
ggplot(conf_matrix, aes(x = Reference, y = Prediction, fill = Freq)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = Freq), color = "black", size = 6) +

9.2 Important Predictors

Based on the decision tree model, the most important predictors for loan approval are:

  1. Credit Score - Most significant factor
  2. Income - Secondary important factor
  3. Debt-to-Income Ratio - Key financial health indicator
  4. Loan Amount - Request amount consideration
  5. Employment Status - Stability indicator

10. Conclusion

The decision tree model provides a transparent and interpretable approach to loan approval prediction. The model achieves reasonable performance and can be used as a baseline for more complex models.
